Here we've loaded the data and made plots of gps time, solar degrees and degrees of latitude vs counts. Initially everything looks messy, but we have a lot of data. We take data every .1 seconds, and we have a 90 minute orbit around the Earth. Below we'll plot an interval of 100000 data points, corresponding to intervals of roughly two orbits, of gps time against solar and latitutde degrees to confirm 54000 data points corresponds to two orbits.
plot(data(1:100000,1),data(1:100000,2),"Linewidth",0.1)
plot(data(1:100000,1),data(1:100000,3),"Linewidth",0.1)
Here we can see that 100000 data points is roughly two solar cycles, and a little less than two orbits which is expected for less than 2*54000 data points, where 54000 data points is one orbit. Taking one orbit as 54000 data points, assuming every orbit is offset from a solar degree cycle by 90 minutes, one solar cycle should be 54000 data points * 22.5hrs/24hrs = 50625 data points, confirming that we are looking at roughly two solar cycles.
Now lets see if our counts are more affected by the periods of the sun or the Earth around our satellite. We'll plot the first 200000 points of data for time, solar degrees and longitudinal degrees against gps time to observe the effects of the solar and Earth periods on our counts.
plot(data(1:300000,1),data(1:300000,4),"Linewidth",0.1)
hold on
plot(data(1:300000,1),data(1:300000,2),"Linewidth",0.1)
plot(data(1:300000,1),data(1:300000,3),"Linewidth",0.1)
hold off
From the above plot we can see that the period of our count data remains consistent with the period of our longitutdinal degree above the Earth, but not with our solar degree. This means we should develop a time-dependent background with a period of 54000 counts, consistent with the period of the Earth around our satellite.
Below is a plot of the first 162000 counts vs. gps time, corresponding to three Earth periods. The first 162000 counts of Earth degrees are also plotted to show the correspondence.
plot(data(1:162000,1),data(1:162000,4),"Linewidth",0.1)
plot(data(1:162000,1),data(1:162000,3),"Linewidth",0.1)
The correspondence between the periods of the counts and Longitudinal degrees is clearly observable - the counts at first glance seem to follow a logarithmic distribution with a period of 54000 counts. We can see the count data beginning a period at 9.40684*10^8 gps time, and two periods later beginning a period at just before 9.40695*10^8 gps time, which is a difference of ~110000 gps data points, or approximately two Earth periods around our satellite. The beginning of the period of our count data seems to be offset from the beginning of our Earth period by 750 seconds, or 7500 data points. This isn't surprising - there's no reason we would necessarily expect the beginning and ends of the periods to coincide, we only observed that there was a correspondence in their length.
What we have in our distribution is counts vs. time. What we want is a distribution of the "counts of counts" - that is, how many of each counts we have, giving us a probability distribution of what this count should be. Because our data is a distribution of positive-valued numbers taken over equal intervals, we should expect it to form a Poisson distribution. We'll want to see how this distribution develops over different iterations, so we'll plot counts vs gps time for the first 54000 data points to see where a period of counts begins and plot our histograms from there. Below are histograms plotted from different count periods, and we can see they do indeed appear to be Poisson distributions. To check we also plotted a Poisson distribution with an equal lambda value to the count distributions for comparison, and it does match our count distribution. Below we'll plot a histogram of the data from one total day - and voila, a Poisson distribution. We can take these from different times of day and use them as pdf's for different times of day

Now that we have probability distributions that match our backgrounds at different times in our count period, we can calculate what a statistically significant measurement would be at different intervals in the count period.
sigma010= poissinv(1 - 2.8665e-7,8.2)
sigma010 = 26
sigma2030 = poissinv(1 - 2.8665e-7,5.9)
sigma2030 = 22
sigma4050 = poissinv(1 - 12.8665e-7,6)
sigma4050 = 21
sigma6070 = poissinv(1 - 2.8665e-7,4.8)
sigma6070 = 19
Above are the count numbers corresponding to a statistically significant measurement for the intervals of 0 to 10 minutes after the count period begins from a peak, the interval of 20 to 30 minutes, 40 to 50 minutes, and 60 to 70 minutes.

Our background appears to be consistent across time and space, with values between values of -1.5 and 1.5, and of a much smaller magnitude of brightness than the stars in the data. This can be observed in the plots of dat(100, :, 5) and dat(100, :, 10), where a signal spike from a star is both consistent over time and of a much greater magnitude than our background, with a value of 4. Our goal is to find a signal source that is present in one of our images, but not in the image above or below it. To do this we can take the difference between every image set of data and the one above it to gain a distribution of the difference between two concurrent images. From that we can determine what a statistically significant signal difference between two concurrent images would be.
